Instead of the global resolution, the Jira issue would have a separate resolution for each fixVersion. 

So if an issue has fixVersions "product A version 1.3", "product A version 2.0" and "product B version 2.0", there would be a separate resolution for each of these. 

That way, one could track this, seeing that the issue is currently resolved for "product A version 1.3" and "product B version 2.0", while still open for "product A version 2.0".

{quote}
We are maintaining several similar products. An issue for one of the products will often be relevant for other products (or several versions of the same product), in which case we set several fixVersions in Jira. The problem is the difficulty of tracking which versions the issue is actually fixed for. Currently we often end up using cloned issues, one for each fixVersion, or "reminder tasks" (port issue so and so to version so and so. But this is, quite frankly, not a good solution at all, it is a hassle, it spreads information over several issues and it does not give a good visibility of the resolution status of the issue.
{quote}

